***********************************************************************************************************************************************************


SWIFT Gateway --->
SWIFT = Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication.
Itâ€™s a global messaging network banks use to securely exchange payment instructions.
It doesnâ€™t transfer money itself, but it ensures the payment instructions reach the right bank in the correct format.

Example: If Bank A (UAE) sends money to Bank B (India), the instructions travel over SWIFT.

 Customer (UAE) --> T24 (Payment Module)
          |
          v
   T24 Outbox (OFS Message)
          |
          v
     SWIFT Gateway
          |
     -----------------------
     |                     |
   SWIFT (Network)      <-- ACK (Accepted)
                        <-- NACK (Rejected)

***********************************************************************************************************************

Temenos Local Development (jBASE, TAFC/TAP, TAFJ)

Q: Whatâ€™s the difference between TAFC and TAFJ, and in what scenarios have you used jBASE?
TAFC (Temenos Application Framework for C) â†’ Runs on jBASE, used for traditional on-prem core banking systems. Itâ€™s lightweight and suitable for legacy deployments.
TAFJ (Temenos Application Framework for Java) â†’ Built on Java, designed for scalability, high availability, and integration with microservices/cloud.
jBASE â†’ I used it for writing local routines, enquiry modifications, OFS message parsing, and creating batch programs.
Example: I built a local routine in jBASE for a custom validation in Funds Transfer (FT), ensuring debit account had sufficient balance before COB posting.

*****************************************************************************************************************************

Q: How does T24 handle the lifecycle of a payment transaction from initiation to settlement?
Initiation â†’ User/system sends request via OFS/API.
Validation â†’ T24 checks account balance, customer status, AML rules.
Booking â†’ Temporary records created in FT application.
Authorization â†’ Dual control or automated STP (Straight Through Processing).
Settlement â†’ Payment message formatted (SWIFT MT/ISO20022 XML) and sent to the clearing system.
Accounting â†’ GL entries generated, balances updated.
Reconciliation â†’ Settlement confirmation, error handling, retry if needed.

*********************************************************************************************************************
What is the difference between SWIFT MT and ISO20022 MX messages in T24 Payments?

SWIFT MT â†’ Legacy format, text-based, widely used in cross-border payments. Example: MT103 (Customer Transfer).
ISO20022 MX â†’ XML-based, structured, richer data, supports regulatory compliance. Example: pacs.008 (Customer Credit Transfer).

**********************************************************************************************************************

OFS message failure with error ACCOUNT.NO.INVALID. How do you troubleshoot?

Check raw OFS message format (field separators, transaction ID).
Validate account number in CUSTOMER/ACCOUNTS application.
Verify local routine validations or field-level controls.
Review jBASE logs or T24 enquiry (ENQUIRY SELECT).
If from API Hub â†’ check API Hub logs, TIF mappings.
Fix root cause (e.g., wrong account, missing currency code).


